segments.text: There we go.
Okay, again, I would point to page 24 to an article entitled Galveston's Conflicting Power Groups by Ed Protz.
Ed is the former grant coordinator for one of those powerful families.
That's the Moody family, and he's written an article basically on the power groups.
I would also...
Draw your attention to page 28 in the same magazine to an article by Harris Kempner.
Mr. Kempner is another member of one of those wealthy influential families.
And his article is entitled The Win-Lose Character of an Island Economy.
And he indicates that two major local issues illustrate how Galveston's economy is inextricably tied to its geography
and foreshadow a third issue yet to come.
So to find out what that third issue is, read the article.
Obviously, there has been, I don't know about religious impact.
Obviously, religion plays a large part.
But as far as city planning goes, I wouldn't say it's not played a greater part, as has political or geographical influences.
Obviously, geographical has been strong because Galveston's a barrier island.
It's a harbor.
That's been the primary trade since day one.
Also because of that, this has been the landing place for many ethnic groups, Italians, Germans, Spanish-speaking cultures, just to name a couple.
Sociological.
Not sure I know what that means.
Economic.
Yeah, I think we touched on economics a little bit.
The ports have always been a strong economic strength of the city.

the other two which are normally mentioned as far as the strengths the second one which is growing very rapidly is the tourist industry and some have predicted that'll be the predominant economic strength in in the near future like within five years the third mainstay of of the local economy is the university of texas medical branch which employs a great deal of people and has been around for
A long time, probably since the turn of the century.
Military, there was an air base here during World War II, but I don't think that was a major influence.
Although one of the issues today does involve the federal government.
Because they do own a large chunk of land, over 700 acres to be exact, on the far eastern part of the island, north of the seawall, which is called the Fort Crockett spoils area.
And that's where all the spoils go as far as the dredging, maintenance dredging, of the Houston Ship Channel, the Galveston Ship Channel, and Galveston Bay.
The issue here is that the city, for years, probably 20 years ago,
made efforts through Senator Jack Brooks, the Corps of Engineers, to have that land released to the city.
Land is a very scarce commodity on a barrier island.
And so we will be starting again very soon another effort to see if we can get those 700 acres released, probably for residential development, largely.
What does this last thing mean?
Is that just a note to you or what is that?
I think that's more of a note to me.
Okay.
No, I think you've touched on everything.
Okay.
Okay.
Well, I sure do thank you for your...
Your information and your time.
Good luck, and I hope Bob gets it done this year.
Because we're not going to help him out financially anymore.
And I was one of those who, I may not be his favorite person, but I said, after a while, you've got to produce something in order to get more money.
But I like Bob, and we have our differences, but I wish him great success in this project.
